article.description: Shannon Johnson made one free throw with 3.2 seconds left and added another with less than a second left to give the Orlando Miracle a 72-70 victory over Phoenix on Saturday night, the Mercury's fourth straight loss.
article.headline: Johnson's free throws in final seconds win it
article.linkText: Johnson delivers Miracle win with late free throws
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Shannon Johnson made one free throw with
3.2 seconds left and added another with less than a second left to
give the Orlando Miracle a 72-70 victory over Phoenix on Saturday
night, the Mercury's fourth straight loss.

	   Katie Douglas led the Miracle (9-6) with 19 points and made the
key steal that led to Johnson's winning free throw.

	   ''To be honest I'm getting tired of these come-from behind
wins,'' Orlando coach Dee Brown said. ''We should be controlling
these games more at home. Phoenix came in hungry for a win and it
looked like they were going to get it.''

	   Gordana Grubin had 23 points and Jennifer Gillom added 21 for
the Mercury (7-8), who dropped to 0-6 on the road this season and
have lost 12 in a row away from home dating to last year.

	   Johnson scored on a driving layup -- her only field goal of the
game in eight attempts -- with 1:29 left to tie the game at 68-all
and complete Orlando's comeback from a 60-53 deficit with 9:48 to
play.

	   Grubin made two free throws with 53 seconds left to give Phoenix
its final lead. Johnson, who finished with seven points, tied it
with two free throws six seconds later.

	   Douglas stole the ball with 21 seconds left and Orlando ran the
clock down until Johnson made the tie-breaking free throw with 3.2
seconds left.

	   ''It seemed like everyone else was hitting for us tonight,''
Johnson said. ''I was focused on making that free throw to win and
I was focused on that layup to tie. That's all that matters is that
I stay focused.''

	   The Mercury used an 11-4 run to take the 60-53 lead with just
under 10 minutes to play.

	   Orlando reverted to its early season style of play by committing
18 turnovers. Over the past six games the Miracle had averaged 12
turnovers, down from the 18 they averaged over the first eight
games of the season.

	   Phoenix led 35-33 at halftime behind 11 points and four rebounds
by Gillom.
